most of this PR is just dealing with the fallout of this deprecation, but I don't see the point. I mean, I realize that `strongRecOn` is `Sort`-valued as opposed to `Prop`-valued, but why not just add a docstring to `strong_induction_on` which says: "This is for proving theorems. If you need to construct data, then use `Nat.strongRecOn`." ?

Then just move `Nat.strong_induction_on` to a different file.

Aha. `Nat.(cases_)strong_induction_on` should still be deprecated, but to `Nat.(cases)strongInductionOn` in `Init.WF`, which I have done. Besides, why would I want to keep a theorem that is a **strictly less general** version of another one and is therefore redundant?
Naming and usage. That is, people will look for the words "strong induction" and use it primarily for proving. If you wish, you can just make it an `alias` of `Nat.strongRecOn`
I am of the opinion that `Nat.strong_induction_on` should be the Prop-valued specialisation of `Nat.strongRecOn`
@YaelDillies do you want me to add the Prop-valued specialisations to my core PR?
I think it's fine to have `strong_induction_on` in mathlib only. If people want to upstream it, they always can

If I reverted this to tactic form with `Nat.strongInductionOn` there would be an error, but `Nat.strongRecOn` from Batteries works in its place. Should I use the latter?

----

The problem is that `Nat.strongInductionOn` in current core has no `@[elab_as_elim]`. I am fixing this in my core PR.
Why are these deprecated? What is replacing them?
`Nat.ltGeByCases` does not have a replacement, but `Nat.ltByCases` is being replaced by `ltByCases` (without namespace).
All the changes in this file (except the very import change are scope creep. Please revert
Please revert, except for the import change obviously
Please revert, except for the import change obviously
Please revert and instead move `strong_induction_on` to `Data.Nat.Defs`
